00:52:00,501 --> 00:52:08,620
Scott: You basically have to ask them questions which require them to say the complicated, you know, insider words.

804
00:52:08,820 --> 00:52:09,081
Scott: Right.

805
00:52:09,141 --> 00:52:17,575
Scott: Like, you know, if you ask them, do you know C++, they'll be like, yes, I have 100 years experience in C++.

806
00:52:18,440 --> 00:52:19,212
Scott: I'm a C++ master.

807
00:52:19,920 --> 00:52:20,201
Scott: Right.

808
00:52:20,823 --> 00:52:28,744
Scott: But if you're like, you know, in C++, you know, what kind of you know, what's your favorite X?

809
00:52:29,327 --> 00:52:32,080
Scott: And they have to actually know what an X is.

810
00:52:32,602 --> 00:52:37,440
Scott: And then, you know, name one and, you know, explain why it's their favorite.

811
00:52:37,560 --> 00:52:46,254
Scott: Like, oh, I like the, you know, the the one in the STL because, you know, this reason or what, you know, they have to actually give a real answer.

812
00:52:46,314 --> 00:53:04,033
Scott: that requires them to say like if you're in the carpeting, the same thing, you know, may ask someone a question where they actually are required to say something about like some sort of wooden structure, you know, as opposed to just saying, yes, I can build stairs, be like, you know, do you like to build stairs in, you know, which?

813
