821
00:53:27,700 --> 00:53:29,580
Rym: Can you work without a graphical environment?

822
00:53:29,740 --> 00:53:30,102
Rym: Just ask.

823
00:53:30,483 --> 00:53:34,000
Rym: So what text editor do you use or what shell do you prefer?

824
00:53:34,181 --> 00:53:37,060
Rym: Because they might say, yeah, I know my way around Linux.

825
00:53:37,201 --> 00:53:42,323
Rym: But if you ask them what shell they prefer, they've got to know the name of at least one shell.

826
00:53:42,343 --> 00:53:44,560
Scott: They got to know what a shell is and they got to be able to name it.

827
00:53:44,640 --> 00:53:47,800
Scott: You know, even if you ask a question like, do you like V.I.

828
00:53:47,980 --> 00:53:48,483
Scott: or Emacs?

829
00:53:48,543 --> 00:53:58,140
Scott: Well, they could just basically say, oh, I like Emacs or oh, I like V.I If you say what text editor to use, they need to know what a text editor is and they need to be able to name a text editor.

830
00:53:58,400 --> 00:54:03,360
Rym: And yeah, and it's also very telling because if they say notepad, then I know better.

831
00:54:03,482 --> 00:54:04,678
Rym: I know that they do not know.

832
00:54:05,040 --> 00:54:05,382
Scott: Yes.

833
00:54:05,582 --> 00:54:10,961
Rym: And if they say Pico, while Pico is silly, at least they know what a text editor is.

834
00:54:10,981 --> 00:54:11,042
Rym: Yep.

835
00:54:12,280 --> 00:54:13,707
Scott: Yeah.

836
00:54:13,988 --> 00:54:16,320
Rym: Sadly, that's pretty much it.

837
00:54:17,061 --> 00:54:17,362
Scott: I think.

838
00:54:17,804 --> 00:54:21,080
Scott: Well, I think the real problem is that if you want to hire a tech person.

839
00:54:21,241 --> 00:54:21,481
Scott: Right.

840
00:54:22,244 --> 00:54:26,560
Scott: But you don't already have a good tech person at your disposal.

841
00:54:26,660 --> 00:54:27,532
Rym: Well, then you're screwed.

842
00:54:27,817 --> 00:54:28,060
Scott: Yeah.

843
00:54:28,180 --> 00:54:33,105
Rym: Well, I guess the only option there is to not go for the technical knowledge route, but to go for the.

844
00:54:33,587 --> 00:54:35,660
Rym: is this person very smart route?

845
00:54:36,640 --> 00:54:40,060
Rym: And it's not hard to figure out if someone is smart by interviewing them.

846
00:54:40,200 --> 00:54:42,419
Rym: Just ask them difficult questions and see how they answer.

847
00:54:42,861 --> 00:54:43,082
Rym: Yeah.

848
00:54:43,683 --> 00:54:59,000
Scott: I think another good thing is if you you might not have like a tech person on staff, but, you know, there are plenty of tech people around who maybe you could like get them to help you out and, you know, be like, hey, is this person smart?

849
00:54:59,161 --> 00:55:03,320
Scott: You know, here is like their resume, you know, or hey, is this person smart?

850
00:55:03,600 --> 00:55:05,059
Scott: I recorded the interview with them.

851
00:55:05,180 --> 00:55:05,965
Scott: Listen to this tape.

852
00:55:06,246 --> 00:55:08,600
Scott: They said some complicated words there.

853
00:55:08,800 --> 00:55:14,879
Scott: They bullshitting, you know, like an RIT when I said plenty of tech people on the Internet who will talk to you.

854
00:55:15,020 --> 00:55:23,783
Rym: I sat in on interviews with like other people to work for the IT department and pretty much like they would always have people sit in and the hospital did the same thing, just technical people.

855
00:55:23,924 --> 00:55:28,910
Rym: Or even when I interviewed at Nature magazine a long time ago, they had a tech guy just sit there.

856
00:55:28,950 --> 00:55:29,940
Rym: He didn't ask any questions.

857
00:55:30,363 --> 00:55:32,339
Rym: He just sat in the room while I talked to the big guy.

858
00:55:32,981 --> 00:55:39,347
Rym: And the only purpose of these people is to after the person leaves, say, yeah, he knows what he's talking about.

859
00:55:39,367 --> 00:55:41,580
Rym: or now he was just using buzzwords.

860
00:55:42,340 --> 00:55:42,561
Scott: Yep.

861
00:55:43,003 --> 00:55:46,600
Rym: And I guess it's really, really obvious to tech people.

862
00:55:46,722 --> 00:55:47,640
Rym: And it's not obvious.

863
00:55:47,942 --> 00:55:49,100
Rym: Well, I mean, it's obvious.

864
00:55:49,240 --> 00:55:53,444
Scott: It's really, you know, we say tech because that's what we are, but it's the same in any profession.

865
00:55:53,625 --> 00:56:03,539
Scott: I mean, if a graphic designer was interviewing, you know, some other graphic designer, they could tell right away if the person was saying like, you know, like, oh, man, what Photoshop filter do you use?

866
00:56:03,680 --> 00:56:12,120
Rym: You know, it's like instead of tech, I guess experts, anyone who's an expert in their field can tell experts in their field from people who don't know their field at all.

867
00:56:12,541 --> 00:56:12,741
Scott: Yeah.

868
00:56:12,781 --> 00:56:14,427
Scott: Now, they can have a real problem.

869
00:56:14,447 --> 00:56:21,140
Scott: if you have someone on your side who is actually a dumb ass, then a smart person comes along.

870
00:56:21,220 --> 00:56:23,719
Scott: The dumb ass will think the smart person is a dumb ass.

871
00:56:24,241 --> 00:56:29,198
Scott: And then you're sort of in a trap, which is, I think, another compounding reason why I.T.

872
00:56:29,800 --> 00:56:34,500
Scott: and, you know, basically tech departments tend to either be all smart or all stupid.

873
00:56:34,981 --> 00:56:41,759
Rym: Yeah, I very rarely run into a case because if it's all stupid, if a smart person gets hired by accident, they get the hell out.

874
00:56:41,941 --> 00:56:44,480
Scott: That's right, because they get pissed off that everything is so stupid.

875
00:56:44,824 --> 00:56:46,079
Scott: They get frustrated and they leave.

876
00:56:46,401 --> 00:56:49,460
Rym: And if it's all smart people, well, the stupid person can't possibly get hired.

877
00:56:49,661 --> 00:56:50,083
Rym: That's right.

878
00:56:50,305 --> 00:56:52,679
Rym: So there's really no way to have a mixed bag I.T.

879
00:56:53,282 --> 00:57:01,676
Rym: unless you have the giant bureaucracy that acts in such a capricious and random way that it hires a 50/50 balance.

880
00:57:02,820 --> 00:57:03,664
Scott: Well, what you can have.

881
00:57:03,704 --> 00:57:09,399
Scott: what can happen a lot of times is a company that has met is big enough as many tech departments.

882
00:57:09,922 --> 00:57:13,720
Scott: So you'll get like this R&D department with all these smart people.

883
00:57:13,800 --> 00:57:21,140
Scott: But then like the people who do all like, you know, the switching for the company network or complete retards, you know, stuff like that can happen.

884
00:57:21,260 --> 00:57:25,840
Scott: But it's or maybe you get like a bunch of like the higher ups in the department.

885
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:27,079
Scott: You know, the department is so big.

886
00:57:27,401 --> 00:57:33,640
Scott: Maybe the CTO and the developers are real smart, but the guys and help desk people are dumb, you know, stuff like that can happen.

887
00:57:34,241 --> 00:57:44,600
Scott: But so honestly, the people actually work together in tech, you know, directly co-workers, you know, who see each other every day and sit next to each other or either all smart or all stupid, most likely.

888
00:57:44,840 --> 00:57:55,199
Rym: The one thing I do want to bring up really quickly before I end this travesty and go to bed is that personality does count for a lot and don't sure does never pick the person who's perfect in every way.

889
00:57:55,802 --> 00:57:58,440
Rym: If when you ask them what they do outside of work, don't have an answer.

890
00:57:58,700 --> 00:57:58,801
Scott: Right.

891
00:57:58,841 --> 00:58:02,100
Scott: Some guy comes in, you'd be like, you know, what's your favorite idea?

892
00:58:02,220 --> 00:58:06,384
Scott: And he's like, oh, I like to use a clips, but real like text that, you know, he knows what he's talking about.

893
00:58:06,746 --> 00:58:09,440
Scott: But then you'd be like, you know, what do you do after work?

894
00:58:09,480 --> 00:58:12,180
Scott: He's like, oh, go home, watch TV, go to bed.

895
00:58:13,041 --> 00:58:20,600
Scott: Don't hire that guy, because I mean, even if he's smart and maybe a work card, you know, is a really boring verse.

896
00:58:20,860 --> 00:58:25,223
Rym: Well, there are two kinds of people who do not really answer when you ask them what they do outside of work.

897
00:58:25,805 --> 00:58:33,660
Rym: One kind is the person who is doing something that they don't want their employer to know about, which is fine, because usually that's something really awesome.

898
00:58:33,980 --> 00:58:34,060
Scott: Yeah.

899
00:58:34,080 --> 00:58:43,340
Scott: It's like the guy's not going to tell you in a job interview that he runs the BDSM dungeon, even though if he does, you should probably hire him because he's totally cool.

900
00:58:43,620 --> 00:58:43,701
Rym: Yeah.

901
00:58:43,722 --> 00:58:45,339
Rym: If I was interviewing someone for an I.T.

902
00:58:45,481 --> 00:58:46,960
Rym: job and I was like, so what do you do outside of work?

903
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:50,840
Rym: And he was like, I run the BDSM dungeon down in Newport.

904
00:58:51,181 --> 00:58:54,520
Scott: I'd be like, you're hired as long as you knew the tech he was talking about.

905
00:58:54,560 --> 00:58:54,803
Scott: Yeah.

906
00:58:54,985 --> 00:58:56,380
Rym: But I'm like, oh, so that's your hobby.

907
00:58:56,480 --> 00:58:57,004
Rym: Anything else?

908
00:58:57,024 --> 00:58:59,000
Rym: And like, yeah, I ski to, you know, people like that.

909
00:58:59,200 --> 00:59:04,940
Rym: But most people I found who don't have an answer actually don't have an answer.

910
00:59:04,980 --> 00:59:10,365
Rym: Like I remember back at the hospital, I was helping interview someone and they were pretty technically qualified.

911
00:59:10,405 --> 00:59:15,160
Rym: But when I asked the guy what he did outside of work and he didn't really have an answer, like he didn't really do anything.

912
00:59:15,261 --> 00:59:18,999
Rym: And the thing he said was, well, I don't really have any hobbies or anything.

913
00:59:20,081 --> 00:59:22,189
Rym: And to which I that always just said.

914
00:59:22,230 --> 00:59:26,300
Scott: that not only tells me that he's a boring person that you don't want to go on that.

915
00:59:26,360 --> 00:59:26,601
Rym: I think.

916
00:59:26,903 --> 00:59:28,371
Rym: So why are you getting a job like?

917
00:59:28,934 --> 00:59:30,040
Rym: is work going to be your life?

918
00:59:30,280 --> 00:59:30,962
Rym: What's your life?

919
00:59:31,444 --> 00:59:36,482
Rym: You work because you have bills to pay to live your real life or have a job.

920
00:59:36,522 --> 00:59:37,026
Rym: That's awesome.

921
00:59:37,066 --> 00:59:39,139
Rym: And the job he was applying for was not awesome.

922
00:59:39,660 --> 00:59:46,860
Rym: Therefore, and he didn't give off the vibe of like, I'm a Russian hacker who's escaping the law and I'm hiding my Russian hacking hobby.

923
00:59:47,581 --> 01:00:00,420
Scott: I mean, if somebody doesn't have a, you know, a thing outside of work that they're working for, then either a their work is it, which means they better be, you know, they better be like the company owner or something where the work is their thing.

924
01:00:00,560 --> 01:00:02,560
Rym: Or it's just that they're passionate about what they're doing.

925
01:00:02,840 --> 01:00:03,264
Scott: Right.

926
01:00:03,304 --> 01:00:05,078
Rym: No one's passionate about low level I.T.

927
01:00:05,300 --> 01:00:05,521
Rym: Right.

928
01:00:06,263 --> 01:00:12,243
Scott: Or or, you know, the question becomes, even if this person can do this job, what's their?

929
01:00:12,385 --> 01:00:13,520
Scott: do they have any motivation?

930
01:00:13,700 --> 01:00:13,921
Scott: Will they?

931
01:00:13,961 --> 01:00:19,899
Scott: will they care that, you know, I mean, like I work because I can have money to do things outside of work.

932
01:00:20,081 --> 01:00:22,660
Scott: If I didn't do anything outside of work, then why would I work?

933
01:00:22,780 --> 01:00:25,760
Scott: I would just be a lazy as bum at work, not caring so much.

934
01:00:26,240 --> 01:00:32,378
Scott: You know, if you have something else you care about and work supports that thing, then that caring transfers over to the work.

935
01:00:32,860 --> 01:00:52,334
Rym: Plus, speaking from experience, the place I work now just is is so much more amazing in terms of just the level of intelligence at all levels compared to everywhere else I've worked and everything else I've ever done in, I guess, in official non GeekNights, you know, working in the real world capacity, which also includes most of my classes, you know, back in school.

936
01:00:52,394 --> 01:00:59,670
Rym: But the one thing that really stands out is that every single person in the place I work, all the technical people, all the like H.R.

937
01:00:59,770 --> 01:01:06,729
Rym: people, everyone, they have like big things they're doing outside of work, like things on the same level of GeekNights for me.

938
01:01:06,890 --> 01:01:16,150
Rym: Like everyone, like they're doing their doctoral theses or they travel the world all the time or they're like a professional chef for fun on the side.

939
01:01:16,450 --> 01:01:22,834
Rym: Like everyone has this full time hobby or this like really big family or something crazy outside of work.

940
01:01:22,874 --> 01:01:27,973
Rym: And work is great and they love their work, but work is just one part of their lives.

941
01:01:28,595 --> 01:01:34,189
Rym: And I noticed that most of the other places I've worked, work seemed to be the only thing these people had.

942
01:01:34,511 --> 01:01:42,580
Rym: Yeah, people would stay late on purpose to not go home to the Y as opposed to staying late because they really want to finish that awesome piece of code they're working on for the algorithm.

943
01:01:42,863 --> 01:01:43,530
Rym: Baphma dad.

